Federal immigration officials have the authority to track down immigrants and noncitizens who have committed certain crimes, months and even possibly years after they've been released, and hold them without bond hearings for potential deportation, the Supreme Court ruled today.
And immigration officials have this authority even if they don't get around to detaining these people for months or even years after the offense was committed.
The ruling does, however, mean that those sweeps where feds come swooping into communities looking for deportable immigrants are potentially even more of a worry for the targets.
Eleven years later, officials for Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) came for him and held him in detention for possible deportation.
That's something of a hint: if similar plaintiffs want such a case heard again, they need to make a constitutional argument.